<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-10-29T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-10-29T01:00:00-05:00" n="653" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d653">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.20/10–2949: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Strong</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-10-29T13:00:00+07:00">October
                                    29, 1949—1 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received October 31—1:59 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Cantel 1245. Understand from Chu Chang-wei that at recent military
                            conference Haikou [<hi rend="italic">Hainan</hi>] Yu Han-mou and Hsueh
                            Yueh agreed defend southwest Kwangtung, Pai to defend south Kwangsi and
                            Chen Chi-tang, Hainan. With regard latter, Chu stated not much to be
                            expected view lack of forces at his disposal. No estimate of forces
                            commanded by Yu and Hsueh.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Strong</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>